Hello Prof. Miller,

=20

Thank you for your evaluation. I have addressed the cons as described =
below and attached the source code files. Apologies for submitting the =
corrections if you do not accept corrections, but given that you are =
trying to provide "industry experience," I am assuming you will accept =
subsequent iterations after the "beta testing."=20

=20

I have addressed the cons below:

*	Not reporting errors after the offending statement.   (This was in the =
specifications)

I misunderstood what "reporting" meant in the specs. I assumed that if =
the error was "reported" to the Errors class by calling RecordError, it =
would count as "reporting" the error. But apparently, you meant printing =
it to the console. This has been fixed now.

*	Should not run emulator if there is an error.=20

You mentioned that translation should continue even after encountering =
an error, so, by extension, I thought you would want the emulator to run =
the program even if there are errors. The fact that the emulator should =
not run after encountering an error is not explicit in the specification =
(to the best of my knowledge).  This has been fixed now.

=20

*	If there is a statement after end, gives misleading error message. =
(=E2=80=9Cmissing end statement=E2=80=9D).=20

This was a bug. This has been fixed now.

=20

*	Does not handle large constants =E2=80=93 stoi will not work for the =
possible size of the constants.=20

I assumed the largest size of the constant to be 99,999. I could not =
find anything on the website that mentions otherwise. Previously, stoi =
exception would be reported, but now, the code reports that the size of =
the constant is invalid.

*	 If there is an extra operand, you repeat the error message twice. =
(Same with some other errors like illegal op code.)=20

The redundancy was intentionally built into the code to detect every =
error encountered during each pass. When logging errors, I feel that it =
is better to record the error that occurs at different places even if it =
is the same cause. To record only once, I would need to make significant =
changes to the fundamental design of the current structure of the code, =
so I will have to pass on this.

*	Does not report a badly formed label =E2=80=93 example: 1hay.

This was entirely my fault; I did not notice the requirement for a label =
name to start with a letter. This has been fixed.

*	Not commenting according to the coding standards.

All functions and classes have been documented with Doxygen comments. =
All enums, dictionaries, and other data structures that define the =
instruction set of the compiler have been commented before them to =
explain their purpose, as required by the standards. As per the comment =
explaining the code, please read my spiel in the next point.

*	 The function DisplaySymbol table in the main does not seem useful =
when it basically calls the same function in the assem object.  (Same =
issue DisplayTranslation)

The function DisplaySymbol and DisplayTranslation serve two main =
purposes:

1.	This increases code readability. This invalidates the need for the =
standard to have a comment for every block of code. If the code needs a =
separate block and a comment to explain the need for the block, it is =
almost always wise to refactor it to a function or a method. This is the =
reason why the project does not need so much commenting because function =
and method names serve the purpose of explaining what the code is doing. =
I hate comments in source code that explain what the code is doing with =
religious ferocity -- they are unreliable and confusing, difficult to =
maintain, and outright UGLY.=20
2.	The functions separate the logic of the program from the interface. =
This is crucial if the project's scope is expanded in the future, say a =
graphical user interface.=20

*	 Not commenting all functions in .cpp files.

All functions have their prototype defined in the header file. Any =
comment in the .cpp file would make it redundant, and if I remember =
correctly the coding standard mentions that the description is only =
necessary for the header file. About explaining the logic of the code =
with comments, see my rant on the previous point.=20

=20

=20

Please feel free to provide any corrections on the above. Thank you very =
much for your support.

